  "prompt": "Does the law prohibit money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, the law prohibits money laundering in most jurisdictions around the world. Money laundering is the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (i.e., \"dirty money\") appear legal (i.e., \"clean\"). This is typically done by disguising the origins of the money through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions.\n\nIn the United States, the primary laws against money laundering include:\n\n1. **The Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) of 1970**: Requires financial institutions to assist government agencies in detecting and preventing money laundering.\n2. **The Money Laundering Control Act of 1986**: Made money laundering a federal crime.\n3. **The USA PATRIOT Act of 2001**: Enhanced anti-money laundering measures, particularly in relation to terrorism financing.\n\nSimilarly, in the European Union, the **Anti-Money Laundering Directives (AMLD)** provide a framework for member states to combat money laundering and terrorist financing. Other countries also have their own specific laws and regulations aimed at combating money laundering, and they often cooperate internationally through organizations like the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**, which sets global standards for anti-money laundering (AML) and counter-terrorist financing (CFT) measures.\n\nPenalties for money laundering can be severe, including substantial fines, imprisonment, and other legal consequences for individuals and organizations involved in such activities.",
